With a little programming know-how, you can use this project to define your own model rocket, and print it. Depending on your printer and how you print your rocket parts, you can print a complete rocket in under two hours. All you have to do is is snap it together, add an engine, and off you go. You can find out more information from the rockit wiki. You can also check out the instructables write up here.

Rockit provides a framework to rapidly generate 3D models of workable model rockets. It leverages OpenSCAD to render rocket part specifications to three dimensional models. This allows you the ability to configure and generate individual model rocket parts suitable for manufacturing on a wide range of 3D printing platforms. With carefully configured parameters, you can design, print and fly your rocket in under two hours. Rockit parses JSON rocket configuration files and writes out to a variety of formats including .json, .scad, .stl, .dxg, .png. It ships with a variety of default templates based on different engine sizes, but these will require local tuning for proper operation. You can find out more information from the rockit wiki. title: Creality CR-10 Taller Z Limit Switch Bracket

description.text: If you have a Creality CR-10 and want to install some cork and foamcore below your heated bed in order to improve heating times, then you're going to need a taller Z limit switch to account or the extra height. Also, you might want to adjust your bed to be level, and then adjust the nozzle height without adjusting all 4 corners of the bed, and this will accomplish that. To use this, simply replace the stock part with this one by removing the z limit switch from the old part, installing it on the printed tall part, and then reinstalling on the machine. Then level the bed and adjust the height of the nozzle to the correct height before locking down the two bolts.

title: Sienci Mill One V2- Prototype Clamping System

description.text:
A powerful CNC needs a powerful clamping solution. This new prototype clamping system for the Sienci Mill One was made in-house with PVC, HDPE, and aluminum.

These prototype machinist clamps will allow you to securely mount material to your Mill One with a very low profile, make your own and let us know what you think!

There is a provided g-code file for modifying your Y gantry to create mounting points. Watch the video to get a better understanding of this process: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wNAAiY-gRc

Some tips when using these clamps:

-> Plan you clamp placement beforehand! This will ensure that the router will not run into the clamps during a milling operation.

-> Securing material on one side can sometimes cause the material to lift up on one side. Double check that the bottom of the material is flat before milling.

-> Use a combination of clamps and double sided carpet tape to create an even more secure workholding combination!

-> Use the flat notches on the top of the clamps for both holding your material down and locking it from moving side-to-side.

-> Try to only use the clamping hole pattern we've provided, any changes made to the file we provide may weaken your Mill One's milling platform.

This is a model of human Glutathione Transferase P1-1 (GSTP1-1). This model is somewhat special to me. It is one of the first structures I solved as a PhD student. Glutathione transferases (aka GSTs)are detoxifying enzymes that catalyze the conjugation of reduced glutathione (GSH), a tripeptide, to xenobiotic substrates, rendering them more soluble. The human pi-class GST, GSTP1-1, consists of two monomers (in green and red in the images). (The STL files contain surface representations of the two monomers "A" and "B".) A third STL file defines a glutathione molecule (in yellow in the images). Each monomer binds one glutathione molecule. Based on PDB entry 5GSS:
http://www.rcsb.org/pdb/explore.do?structureId=5gss STL files created using VMD:
http://www.ks.uiuc.edu/Research/vmd/

description.text:
This is a dual 24" monitor stand I have designed to be 3D printable.
****Use this at your own risk***. If you don't understand basic structural design concepts and are a beginner at 3D printing I do not suggest you attempt this project. I am not responsible for you damaging your screens! As always, a reminder that people take time to design and share models with you free of charge, therefore please upload photos of makes (you don't want me to start selling them instead do you?) :)

I'm finding I can get really good strength of parts (it's all about how you design and orientate for printing). Print high infill. Solid infill for Monitor mount sections. At least 33% infill everywhere else. Leave the orientation of parts as is. They are this way so that the stress is carried across multiple layers, not across the grain (i.e. layers don't like direct shear forces applied to them). the screenshot is with my 24" screen and 19" older screen. Seems to work.  
This is a work in progress as I haven't printed it yet, but I know it will work. Provide a steel pipe to mount to, (designed for some 33.6mm thick walled stainless pipe I have lying around - odd size I know it's imperial). The bolt sizes are 8mm, use locknuts. Glue and screw the monitor mount together (unfortunately this is the only way to make sure the part is good in torsion, shear and bending).

comments.text: Do you think that doing the Acetone Vaporing will these part give it more strength?
comments.author: Korrupt3dazn

comments.text:
Acetone Vaporing will improve the overall layer to layer adhesion, however it will alter the structural properties of the material (namely removing the Styrene component from the outermost surface). I've designed these parts to print orientated so that the stress is carried by the layer, not across (leading to delamination). I think some vaporing will mainly just improve the surface finish, as I haven't created any thin sections where a minor change in functional cross-section would cause it to fail.
I ended up buying a dual stand for $60 on ebay. All the rest were way too expensive, hence why I was looking at a 3D printable version. Mind you I have modified the steel one I bought with 3D printed parts ;).

title: 1.5mm Bed Z-Axis Spacer for BIBO Dual Touch X

description.text: This is a snap on 1.5mm bed spacer to lower your bed on the Z-Axis for adding things like PEI sheets above the glass or if you have a bed that can't adjust low enough to level properly. You might want to add supports on the overhang to make it print cleaner. I just whipped this up really quick today but it works perfectly as is. If you use the gcode without slicing 1st layer height is at 120% since my bed wouldn't lower enough without the spacer so you might need to re-slice if your bed is normal already.

comments.text: The spacer just snaps onto the back of the bed frame from right where the z-axis end stop switch hits the frame. You should have a rectangular cutout in the frame that the alignment block snaps into. Due to variations in production you might have to trim just a hair off the edge of that alignment block to get it to snap on. I have almost 500 hours of print time using this to space the bed and it works perfectly to give you that extra adjustment room

Video: https://www.youtube.com/edit?o=U&video_id=Jm4h6dKwD3c

It is picked up from its base, (which is designed to sit on a 96-well plate - glue on if using properly) and used to move eppendorf tubes from one spot to another (they will need to have quite a large amount of their height exposed so that the grabber can get around them). The tool is then ejected back onto the base for re-use.

This would need a nice extension to the Python library - I did everything with 'points' for the demo.

Why? Because we can, and because one day it might be useful for:

  • centrifuging
  • heat shock
  • old-style water bath PCR?!

Build your own light-up bo staff for bojutsu or fun at music festivals! Full instructions can be found on my blog, here:
http://uselesspuzzles.blogspot.com/2012/07/how-to-make-led-light-up-bo-staff-for.html Print these files with translucent PLA and they will slide right in to 3/4" PVC pipe!

I had about 15 people come up to me over the weekend (at Electric Forest // Rothbury) and ask me where I got my LED staff and how much I paid for it. It seems I'm not the only one frustrated that there's only really one LED staff on the market and it costs about $180! So, here are instructions to make your own collapsible LED bo staff for about $25! Building requires about 15 minutes time, a trip to Home Depot, and connection pieces from this page. You'll need to print them in clear/natural so they are translucent. You can also buy them from me (or buy an entire finished staff :) using the PayPal button in my blog.
  • Gather the following supplies:
    • -2x 2' long 3/4" thick PVC pipe (pre-cut at Home Depot) - $1.39 ea/
    -3x Glow Wands (can find at Sears, Home Depot, Amazon, etc) - $2-5 ea/
    -Electrical tape (whatever colors you prefer) - $3 ea/
    -Translucent endcaps, middle, & connectors - print 2 endcaps and 4 connectors

  • Remove the LED + battery assembly from the glow wands, and secure the batteries in place with electrical tape

  • Place the LED inside each endcap and the middle piece, then insert the connector pieces

  • Wrap the PVC in whatever tape you'd like, or paint it whatever color(s) you wish:

  • Now pop in the endcaps and connect the two PVC pieces with the middle piece!

  • Congratulations! You now have a lightweight, collapsible, awesome-looking LED staff you made yourself for under $30 :)

description.text:
This is the same as my other Basic Projects, standard parts that you
can combine and build the way you like.

It is not an exact scalemodel with all details. The important thing is
that it should be easy to print and be functional.

The measurements comes from Lenz 42901 (picture borrowed
from Lenz), a freight car chassie for "selbstbau",
do it your self - type. It is no longer available but I was lucky
and found one to buy. I'm going to use this as a standard
2-axle chassie and I made it in three different lengths. All other
parts are the same.

It is designed to run on commercial track from Lenz/Peco and with
other commercial rolling material from Lenz/Brawa.
That's why I use couplings from Lenz.

Youtube video:
https://youtu.be/xaxWYJf50NU

Parts required:
Axle, 3mm threaded rod, about 46mm long.
M3 nuts (and washers)
M2 assortment
2 x Lenz 49013 couple holder
2 x Lenz 49010 coupler
glue (I use Loctite Super Glue GEL)

Chassie comes in three different lenghts (total length with bumpers):
LOB 180mm, chassie-length 154mm, wheelbase 80mm
LOB 200mm, chassie-length 174mm, wheelbase 100mm
LOB 220mm, chassie-length 194mm, wheelbase 120mm

Axleholder comes in two different types.
3mm axle (M3 threaded rod)
2mm axle (original Lenz axle and wheels, art.nr. 49025)

Coupler pocket is made for Lenz 49013 couple holder and
Lenz 49010 coupler.
There is also 1mm mountingplates to get the coupler in level.
Tempmount is just for holding coupling in place until you get
something to put on the chassie.

The models were originally a pretty close remix to "Landru's Modular Model Rocket". But due to all the major changes, I don't qualify it as a remix of his model rocket, I'll keep the remix tag though, so people easier can compare it with the original rocket.

Rocket Aurora is not just "a rocket model", this model will become a part of a fully customizable rocket system. To make this possible I need to get YOUR feedback on things that are incorrect/should be improved or just new ideas!

NOTE:

  1. The example models are not meant to be printed out! They are just there as inspiration. Open .zip file in the "files folder" to get to the STL files.
  2. An Arduino Uno (Raspberry Pi 3/2, not tested) + ONE 9 volts battery + some small measurement instruments, fit in the Payload Bay, depending on how big "Payload Body Tubes" being used.

NEW:

  • Special Engine mounts Adapters (32 --> 24mm)

Package contains:

  • Large Body Tube + Payload version
  • Medium Body Tube + Payload version
  • Small Body Tube + Payload version
  • Payload Adapter
  • Payload Coupler (Only needed in special cases)
  • Dual Female Adapter
  • Dual Male Adapter
  • Ogive Nosecone + Payload version
  • Conical Nosecone + Payload version
  • Nosecone Coupler + Payload version
  • Engine Holder 32mm + Adapters
  • Engine Upper Stop 32mm + Adapters
  • Blank Fincan
  • Fincan 24mm
  • Fincan 18mm
  • Fincan Angled 2xCluster 18mm
  • Camera Mount 22mm (https://www.gearbest.com/car-dvr/pp_314031.html)
  • Dual, Mirrored, Empty fincan adapter

Coming Soon:

  • Launchpad (will come as a separate design)

Instructions:
Step 1:
Select Components. You will need at least nosecone, body tube, fincan, and nosecone coupler. You can use multiple body tubes fincans to make a longer and more steady rocket if desired

Step 2:
Print parts. They printed with the perfect tightness on printer. You may need to sand some mating surfaces or add tape for the correct fit.

Step 3:
Screw nosecone to coupler. Glue if needed

Step4:
Tie the nosecone coupler to the fin can through the body tube with 3ft of non-flammable cord. Attach a parachute or streamer if desired (HIGHLY RECOMMENDED)

Step 5:
Insert Motor and add short drywall screw to the rear of the rocket for motor retention. You can also put tape on the rocket motor for a tight friction fit.

Or if you use a homemade rocket engine, (only 32mm outer diameter compatible for the moment). Use an empty fincan with an Engine holder 32mm put directly on top of it. Then place body tubes between and when preferred put the engine stop to prevent it to shoot up through the rocket.

Step 6:
Fly safely and have fun! (Be sure that you are at a safe distance from houses and such things to prevent damaging others property or people).

Using crackle paint

description.text:
Lasercut Penrose Puzzle in a likewise lasercut box. A birthday present for a very smart 9 y/o girl, who's an uber puzzler.

Remix of Flex box, which is a remix of Parametric Flexbox. Cut in 3 mm plywood. The puzzle is a remix of Penrose Snap Tiles. The "thin rhombuses" are cut in clear acrylic, the "thick ones" in red (both 3mm).

It's a fascinating puzzle. There's five-fold rotational symmetry, but unlike square, triangular and hexagonal tilings it is non-periodic. It NEVER repeats. See Wikipedia for more background.

Twenty thick and fifteen thin pieces are useful for a small puzzle. There are ten pieces in the SVG file called thin star, but only five in the thick star. In general, more thick than thin pieces are needed. In a really big puzzle, the ratio of the thick rhombuses to the thin ones is the golden ratio 1.618...

description.text: Continuing the theme of fractals that print with their own support structures, this is a model of the Sierpinski tetrix, a fractal based on the tetrahedron. It's a difficult object for a fused-filament printer because it involves lots of bridges, and the individual tetrahedra are only lightly connected to each other. To make this model I started with cgranade's OpenSCAD Recursive Sierpinski Tetrahedron, which includes a clever adaptation for 3D printing, a parameter that adjusts the adhesion between adjacent tetrahedra. It makes the tetrix less like the mathematical ideal, but a perfect model isn't printable anyway. I added external support that lets the model print upside-down, which solves the bridging problem. See the instructions for how to customize it and suggestions on how to get a good print.

The Customizer parameters are as follows:

  • Order - the level of recursion of the fractal. Zero is a solid tetrahedron, and the script will work up to 6, but I've limited it to 4 in Customizer to reduce the load on the servers because I don't think anything beyond that level is likely to be printable.

  • Size - the length of a side of the tetrix, but note that the size varies a little with different levels of recursion, and will need adjustment if you want exact results.

  • Adhesion - the adjustment (from cgranade's original code) that allows a connection between adjacent tetrahedra. I've found 0.25 to be a reasonable starting value, you can try setting it lower (less adhesion, but a more ideal fractal).

  • Intersection - the amount that the support structure overlaps with the tetrix. This is not in millimeters because it's applied before the scaling. At a size of 80 mm, 0.005 produces a solid structure that isn't too hard to remove.
    • I'd suggest starting with the defaults. Smaller prints may be possible but I've found that my printer inevitably knocks some of the small tetrahedra loose, and the print is ruined. It's likely that the OpenSCAD output will need to be repaired before it can be sliced. For the example STL file, I used Netfabb Cloud. I've had success with these parameters, and with the following settings in Slic3r: 0.30 mm layers
    3 perimeters
    3 top and bottom layers
    avoid crossing perimeters
    0% infill
    0 solid layers
    0 mm solid infill threshold area This keeps the printer from spending too much time on each small tetrahedron, and seems to make the whole model more stable. The resulting print has 14 g of plastic in the finished tetrix and 21 g in the supports, but they're already quite minimal and I'm not sure how to make them smaller and still have them work. To remove the supports it's best to hold the model gently but firmly and slowly rock the support back and forth, only bending it just a very small amount until the plastic begins to break loose. Other than that the model should need no cleanup.

I really like ttocsneb's Pi Zero4U case and he was nice enough to post the STEP files for easy modification. I had an older Adafruit 2.8in TFT touchscreen for a Raspberry Pi 1 A/B with the old 13x2 GPIO header that I haven't been using but wanted to. This case was perfect to modify to also enclose the TFT. It sits nicely on the RPi Zero GPIO header, and when on sits nicely at a good viewing angle. I just needed to mod those STEP files, Thanks ttocsneb !!!!

This case, TFT screen combo is very minimalistic, but that is also what I like so much about it. It functions well, and provides a good viewing angle when using the TFT screen. I have provided my STEP files, and so has ttocsneb, so this design can be modified as much as anyone wants. I really look forward to seeing how others might modify the design and use it as a basis to customize it for their uses. STEP files can be opened in many design software packages, including the FREE to use AutoDesk's Fusion 360.

I am already considering customizing the open space below the TFT screen to include the components needed to run this setup off of a rechargeable battery. Snap fit would also be great, as ttocsneb's original design snaps together great. The TFT screen makes this difficult, but I think it could be done given enough thought.

The first number in the file names references what changes I made. I have included STL's and STEP files, both have the same names:

  1. I opened the GPIO cutout, deepening it 1mm into the interior of the body and added the back plate for mounting the TFT display. I also opened the HDMI and micro USB openings, raising them up 1mm each.

  2. Everything is the same as #1, but I also enclosed the GPIO header cutout to give the case a cleaner look now that the GPIO's are in use that aligns with the enclosure of the TFT. This is the one I printed, but is identical to #1 aside from enclosing the GPIO cutout.

  3. This is the enclosure or wall that surrounds and protects the TFT when mounted. The TFT also rests on the pads on the interior of the walls giving it support when using the touchscreen. This needs to be put in place before seating the TFT on top of it and aligning and mounting the GPIO header.

  4. This is the Bezel that sits on top of and covers the TFT, exposing only the screen and buttons of the TFT. It protects the TFT and covers up the exposed GPIO pins soldered to the TFT making it look clean and keeping fingers out of the electrically live connections. This bezel also has printing between the buttons of the TFT.

  5. This is the same Bezel as #4 but without the printing between the buttons of the TFT.

The portion of the case that goes over the Zero4U USB hub was not modified in any way. It can be found with the Original Zero4U case by ttocsneb.

I have secured the entire modification to the case with three 2mm nylon bolts 20mm long and nylon nuts.

Enjoy-
Matt

Bolt it up and hop over to Adafruit to get your TFT set up with their custom made drivers, using their tutorial.

The tutorial is for running RetroPie, but if you follow the directions under PiTFT Setup, it works well with most Distro's. I have found it is easier to setup the RPi when connected to an HDMI display, and after the drivers are installed then connect the TFT display. Unfortunately I also found out that my micro HDMI to HDMI adapter would not fit once I had assembled all of the parts for this case and TFT combo. But, I also like to SSH into my RPi to install the drivers as this makes following the tutorial easier and I avoid mistyping terminal prompts by just using copy/paste on the computer I am accessing the RPi from. A tutorial on how to use SSH is provided by Adafruit.

When you begin the process of installing the drivers you will do some pre-configuration via an onscreen number menu that looks like this:

There will be four choices you will need to make, here are the selections I made to orient the screen as I did in the pictures of the case when assembled.

Select Project: In the picture above, from the Adafruit tutorial, it only shows two options. When I entered this configuration menu there were actually four options. Regardless of how many options there are, SELECT the OPTION to: Configure options manually. When I did this, it was option #4.

Select Display Type: here you will want to select: PiTFT / PiTFT Plus 2.8" Capacitive. When I did this, it was option #3.

HDMI Rotation: here you will want 90º counterclockwise portrait. When I did this, it was option #2. This may seem wrong, but this is what worked best for me with the hardware I used as specified at the beginning. I will discuss why this worked for me, in my opinion further down the instructions.

TFT (MADCTL) rotation: not really sure what this is, but here you will want to select 0º rotation. When I did this, it was option #1.

After you make these four pre-configuration selections the TFT screen drivers will begin to download and configure. When the whole process is completed you will be prompted to select: Do you want to reboot now? yes/no when I did this, I selected "n" for no because now you want to shutdown the RPi and install the TFT screen. You can shut down the RPi from the terminal prompt by typing:

sudo shutdown -h now

This will shutdown the RPi, give it enough time to fully complete the shutdown and then unplug the RPi PSU and place the TFT screen and printed parts on the RPi by seating the GPIO header on the TFT screen onto the GPIO pins of the RPi. When this is complete you can plug the PSU back into the RPi and let it boot back up. With the new TFT screen this will take a while before you see anything as the driver must be loaded which is further into the boot cycle than HDMI. You will not see most of the scrolling txt that you see when connected to HDMI, but don't worry, if your TFT is working properly it will all boot up fine and the display will begin showing graphics or txt when the driver is loaded based on the OS distro you are using.

I have used a couple of Adafruit's TFT screens, 2.8" and 3.5". When I get them installed and configured with the drivers I have noticed that graphics and txt seem stretched horizontally or squished vertically. I have tried a variety of configurations to get the TFT to display properly. If you look in the Adafruit tutorial there is a section titled "Rescaling" which lists the resolution of the screen as 320x240, I have found that if changed to 240x320 the graphics and txt appear normal and no longer appear stretched vertically or squished horizontally. I am not sure if the resolution of 320x240 is a typo mistake on Adafruit's part, but I know that the change to 240x320 to me makes the display appear correct. As I mentioned earlier, setting your display up in the pre-configuration to "90º counterclockwise portrait" seemed wrong, as the display is actually in landscape mode when configured as I outlined, I believe this is because when the tutorial was written up the resolution was written in reverse order as 320x240 but is actually 240x320. Making this change in my opinion displays the correct aspect when displayed on the TFT, and how to do this is outlined in Adafruit's tutorial.

If you have any questions or comments, please post them. It is always good to get feedback.

Enjoy-
Matt

description.text:
An Elbonian (Yorgi or Yergi or Yugi, if you like), from the Dilbert comic strip by Scott Adams.

Elbonia is a "developing" nation waist-deep in mud. Dogbert once became the king of Elbonia, but Dilbert convinced him to abdicate. Elbonians all look alike (to me), in a national costume of a robe, tall hat, and bushy beard.

No supports are required. If you have the right filament colors, no painting is needed.

The completed model is in proportion to the Dilbert, Wally, Pointy Haired Boss and Dogbert models from the comic that have been previously posted by @reddadsteve.

I went through several variations; the final model is the grey one in the middle of the photo.
Enjoy!

No

No

10%

Notes:

Brims are needed for the hands.
All parts are presented here in the right orientation for printing.

OnShape.com design

https://cad.onshape.com/documents/2d3ae25e05fa8ea6c95a0371/w/90b2db758c33107dfef5c284/e/4423013ec4e62bf2c7cea9b9

Or search Public projects for Elbonian.

I used a lot of volumes lofted from splines to make the beard, face, robe and other parts. The initial outline shapes were traced from the GIF image.

Some parts (hands, robe) were based on the PHB by Steve.

There were a lot of iterations in the design process.

sleeve_L

Assembly tips:

-Assembling the model is quite straightforward.
-The model is meant to be glued together.
-Some of the pieces have tight clearances. Take care to ensure that the first layer 'squish' and any added brim is completely cleaned off.
-The key alignment piece is the mouth. The upright part fits into the recess in the face and the moustache. There's also a recess for it in the beard. The tops of the mouth, face, and beard should all align.
-There is a recess round the top of the face/beard combo for the hat. The hat is round.
-Be sure to completely test fit the face/moustache/mouth/beard combo before gluing any of the pieces.
The fit around the bottom of the beard and top of the sleeves is tight.

description.text:
This is an assistive device designed to help a person with a transradial amputation swing a baseball bat. It was designed by members of eNable Lowell, an on-campus group at the University of Massachusetts Lowell that designs and distrbutes 3D printed assistive devices to people with limb differences.
Note: The device was designed with a wiffle ball bat in mind. It has not been tested on heavier wood or aluminum baseball bats.

Post-Print Assembly

Sand any rough edges and remove support material.
Cut and apply polyurethane foam to inside of gauntlet
Use a soldering iron to heat up the inserts and push them into the gauntlet. Make sure the inserts are level with the top surface of the gauntlet. Let them cool before threading in screws.
Install rubber rod in flex adaptor and bat holder.
Use a 3mm drill bit to drill through the rubber on both the flex adaptor and bat holder, using the printed holes as a guide.
Pass an M3 screw through the hole in the rubber, and use a nut to secure the rubber rod in the flex adaptor and the bat holder.
Mount flex adaptor to gauntlet.
Press bat into bat holder.
Pass velcro straps through side slots.
Play Ball!

Materials

Hardware:
3x M3 Heat Set Inserts
2x M3 Nuts
5x M3 Socket head Cap Screws
Rubber Rod
Polyurethane Foam w/ adhesive backing
Velcro Straps
(All materials can be purchased from McMaster-Carr or Amazon)
